## Project Structure

```
kairos/
├── cmd/
│   └── server/
│       └── main.go                # Entry point
├── internal/
│   ├── api/
│   │   ├── handler.go             # HTTP handlers
│   │   ├── middleware.go           # Logging, auth, metrics
│   │   └── router.go              # Route definitions
│   ├── classifier/
│   │   ├── model.go               # ONNX model loading & inference
│   │   ├── tokenizer.go           # Tokenization (or call into Python)
│   │   └── classifier.go          # Pipeline 3 interface
│   ├── matcher/
│   │   ├── exact.go               # Exact match lookup
│   │   ├── regex.go               # Regex pattern matching
│   │   ├── fuzzy.go               # Levenshtein / fuzzy matching
│   │   ├── token_overlap.go       # Token overlap scoring
│   │   └── matcher.go             # Pipeline 1 interface (orchestrates all)
│   ├── search/
│   │   ├── meilisearch.go         # Meilisearch client & federated query
│   │   └── scorer.go              # Result aggregation by product index
│   ├── aggregator/
│   │   ├── weights.go             # Dynamic weight computation
│   │   └── aggregator.go          # Score merging & ranking
│   ├── fallback/
│   │   └── llm.go                 # LLM reranker for low-confidence cases
│   ├── products/
│   │   ├── registry.go            # Product registry (loads variant JSON files)
│   │   └── variants.go            # Variant data structures
│   └── config/
│       └── config.go              # Configuration loading
├── tools/
│   └── variant_generator/
│       ├── main.py                # CLI entry point
│       ├── generator.py           # Core generation logic
│       ├── keyboard.py            # Keyboard adjacency model
│       ├── phonetic.py            # Phonetic variant generation
│       ├── misspelling.py         # Transposition & common error generation
│       └── expander.py            # Abbreviation expansion
├── training/
│   ├── extract_kb_data.py         # Pull all KB articles from Meilisearch
│   ├── generate_synthetic.py      # LLM-based synthetic query generation
│   ├── prepare_dataset.py         # Combine, clean, split into train/val/test
│   ├── train.py                   # Fine-tune classifier model
│   ├── evaluate.py                # Evaluate on test set, confusion matrix
│   ├── export_onnx.py             # Export trained model to ONNX
│   └── quantize.py                # INT8 quantization
├── data/
│   ├── variants/                  # Generated variant JSON files (one per product)
│   │   ├── datto_bcdr.json
│   │   ├── it_glue.json
│   │   ├── vsa.json
│   │   └── ...
│   ├── training/                  # Training datasets (gitignored)
│   │   ├── raw/
│   │   ├── synthetic/
│   │   └── final/
│   └── models/                    # Trained model artifacts (gitignored)
│       ├── kairos_classifier.onnx
│       └── kairos_classifier_int8.onnx
├── config/
│   ├── config.yaml                # Service configuration
│   └── products.yaml              # Product registry (canonical names, IDs, descriptions)
├── docker/
│   ├── Dockerfile                 # Production image
│   └── Dockerfile.training        # Training environment with Python + PyTorch
├── Makefile
├── go.mod
├── go.sum
└── README.md
```

**Language Split:**

- **Go:** The entire runtime service (API, pipelines, aggregator, serving)
- **Python:** Offline tooling only (variant generator, training pipeline, model export)
- **No Python at runtime** — the trained model runs via ONNX Runtime's Go bindings

---

## Implementation Phases

### Phase 1: Foundation & Variant Generator

**Goal:** Build the offline tooling that generates the matching database.

**Tasks:**

```
1.1  Set up project structure (Go module, Python virtualenv, directory layout)
1.2  Create products.yaml with all 42 products (canonical name, ID, description, known abbreviations)
1.3  Build keyboard adjacency graph (QWERTY layout → neighbor map)
1.4  Build transposition engine (swap adjacent chars, double-letter reduction/expansion)
1.5  Build phonetic variant generator (Soundex/Metaphone baseline + custom rules)
1.6  Build abbreviation expander (input: abbreviation map, output: expanded forms)
1.7  Build slang/informal generator (configurable per product)
1.8  Build regex pattern generator (combine variants into flexible patterns)
1.9  Wire all generators into CLI tool: input product name → output full variant JSON
1.10 Run generator on all 42 products
1.11 Manual review pass — prune bad variants, add missing ones
1.12 Write tests for each generator component
```

**Deliverable:** `data/variants/` populated with reviewed JSON files for all 42 products.

---

### Phase 2: Pipeline 1 — Regex & Fuzzy Matcher

**Goal:** Build the fastest pipeline. Exact matches, regex, fuzzy, and token overlap.

**Tasks:**

```
2.1  Define PipelineResult struct and Pipeline interface in Go
2.2  Build product registry loader (reads all variant JSON files on startup)
2.3  Build exact match index (lowercase variant → product_id hash map)
2.4  Build regex matcher (pre-compile all patterns on startup)
2.5  Build fuzzy matcher (Levenshtein distance against all variant strings)
2.6  Build token overlap scorer
2.7  Wire all matchers into Pipeline 1 orchestrator (run in order, collect results)
2.8  Benchmark: validate < 1ms latency on realistic inputs
2.9  Write tests with known product mentions, misspellings, and edge cases
```

**Deliverable:** Working Pipeline 1 that returns scored product matches for any input string.

---

### Phase 3: Pipeline 2 — Meilisearch Integration

**Goal:** Use federated search across all KB indexes as a classification signal.

**Tasks:**

```
3.1  Set up Meilisearch client in Go
3.2  Implement federated search call (query all indexes, get top K results)
3.3  Build result scorer (aggregate by source index, normalize scores)
3.4  Calculate confidence gap between top two products
3.5  Handle edge cases: empty results, single-index results, timeout
3.6  Benchmark latency against live Meilisearch instance
3.7  Write tests with mock Meilisearch responses
```

**Deliverable:** Working Pipeline 2 that returns product scores from KB search relevance.

---

### Phase 4: Training Data Pipeline

**Goal:** Extract KB data and generate a labeled dataset for the classifier.

**Tasks:**

```
4.1  Write Meilisearch extraction script (pull all docs from all 42 indexes)
4.2  Parse and clean article content (titles, headers, body text, tags)
4.3  Create direct training examples from article titles and headers
4.4  Build synthetic query generator (LLM batch call to generate user-like queries per article)
4.5  Run synthetic generation across all products (budget: ~$5-15 in API costs)
4.6  Combine all sources into unified dataset (text, product_id)
4.7  Analyze class distribution, identify imbalanced products
4.8  Stratified split into train/validation/test (80/10/10)
4.9  Save as Parquet or CSV files in data/training/final/
4.10 Document dataset statistics (total examples, per-class counts, avg length)
```

**Deliverable:** Clean, labeled, split dataset ready for model training.

---

### Phase 5: Pipeline 3 — Train & Deploy Classifier

**Goal:** Train, evaluate, export, and integrate the classification model.

**Tasks:**

```
5.1  Set up training environment (PyTorch, transformers, ONNX)
5.2  Implement dataset loader with tokenization
5.3  Build model: MiniLM base + classification head
5.4  Implement training loop with class-weighted loss
5.5  Train model, monitor validation loss for early stopping
5.6  Evaluate on test set: accuracy, per-class precision/recall/F1
5.7  Generate confusion matrix — identify commonly confused product pairs
5.8  Iterate: augment training data for weak classes, retrain
5.9  Export final model to ONNX
5.10 Quantize to INT8, benchmark accuracy loss (should be negligible)
5.11 Integrate ONNX Runtime in Go service
5.12 Implement tokenizer in Go (or use a Go tokenizer library)
5.13 Build Pipeline 3 interface: input message → output scored predictions
5.14 Benchmark inference latency (target: < 5ms)
5.15 Write integration tests
```

**Deliverable:** Working Pipeline 3 running ONNX model in Go with < 5ms inference.

---

### Phase 6: Score Aggregator & API

**Goal:** Merge all pipeline results and expose the classification API.

**Tasks:**

```
6.1  Implement static weight aggregation
6.2  Implement dynamic weight adjustment logic
6.3  Implement confidence thresholding (high/medium/low)
6.4  Wire all three pipelines to run concurrently (goroutines)
6.5  Build aggregator that collects results and produces final ranking
6.6  Build HTTP handler for POST /api/v1/classify
6.7  Build debug response format
6.8  Build health and metrics endpoints
6.9  Add request logging and latency tracking
6.10 End-to-end integration test: message in → ranked products out
6.11 Load test: validate performance under concurrent requests
```

**Deliverable:** Complete API returning classified products with < 20ms p95 latency.

---

### Phase 7: LLM Fallback & Polish

**Goal:** Handle low-confidence cases and production-harden the service.

**Tasks:**

```
7.1  Implement LLM fallback client (Azure OpenAI or Anthropic API)
7.2  Build reranking prompt with candidate products from aggregator
7.3  Implement fallback trigger (only when confidence < threshold)
7.4  Add fallback latency to response
7.5  Rate limiting and circuit breaker for LLM calls
7.6  Dockerfile for production deployment
7.7  Configuration via environment variables and config file
7.8  Structured logging (JSON format for log aggregation)
7.9  Graceful shutdown handling
7.10 README with setup, configuration, and deployment instructions
```

**Deliverable:** Production-ready service with LLM fallback for edge cases.

---

### Phase 8: Evaluation & Tuning

**Goal:** Validate accuracy on real traffic and optimize.

**Tasks:**

```
8.1  Collect sample of real Ada chat messages (manually labeled with correct product)
8.2  Run evaluation suite: measure accuracy, precision, recall per product
8.3  Identify failure modes: which products are most confused?
8.4  Tune aggregation weights based on evaluation results
8.5  Tune confidence threshold to minimize fallback rate while maintaining accuracy
8.6  A/B test against current Kairos implementation (if applicable)
8.7  Monitor fallback rate in production — target < 5%
8.8  Set up feedback loop: log low-confidence cases for review and retraining
8.9  Document per-product accuracy and known weaknesses
```

**Deliverable:** Validated, tuned system with documented accuracy metrics.

---

## Configuration

```yaml
# config/config.yaml

server:
  port: 8080
  read_timeout: 5s
  write_timeout: 5s

pipelines:
  regex_fuzzy:
    enabled: true
    variants_dir: "./data/variants"
    fuzzy_min_similarity: 0.75
    fuzzy_max_distance: 2
  
  meilisearch:
    enabled: true
    host: "http://meilisearch:7700"
    api_key: "${MEILI_API_KEY}"
    search_limit: 10          # top K results to analyze
    timeout: 500ms
  
  classifier:
    enabled: true
    model_path: "./data/models/kairos_classifier_int8.onnx"
    tokenizer: "sentence-transformers/all-MiniLM-L6-v2"
    max_seq_length: 128
    top_k: 5

aggregator:
  base_weights:
    regex_fuzzy: 0.40
    meilisearch: 0.25
    classifier: 0.35
  confidence_thresholds:
    high: 0.80
    low: 0.50
  dynamic_weighting: true

fallback:
  enabled: true
  provider: "anthropic"       # or "azure_openai"
  model: "claude-sonnet-4-20250514"
  timeout: 3s
  max_retries: 1

logging:
  level: "info"
  format: "json"

metrics:
  enabled: true
  path: "/api/v1/metrics"
```

---

## Success Criteria

| Metric | Target |
|---|---|
| Overall accuracy (top-1) | ≥ 95% |
| Overall accuracy (top-3) | ≥ 99% |
| p95 latency (without fallback) | < 20ms |
| p95 latency (with fallback) | < 2000ms |
| LLM fallback rate | < 5% |
| Cost per classification | ~$0.00 (LLM fallback only) |
| Cold start time | < 5s (model + variant loading) |
| Memory footprint | < 500MB |

---

## Future Considerations

- **Feedback loop:** Log all classifications with confidence scores. Flag low-confidence results for human review. Use corrections as additional training data. Retrain classifier periodically.
- **Product additions:** When a new product is added (product 43+), run variant generator, add KB articles to Meilisearch, retrain classifier with new class. Pipelines 1 and 2 can be updated without retraining.
- **Multi-label classification:** Some messages might relate to multiple products (e.g., integration between BMS and IT Glue). Consider supporting multi-label output in a future version.
- **Contextual classification:** Use conversation history (previous messages in the chat) as additional context for classification. Requires changes to the API contract and model architecture.